\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 4.           Calystegia}             R.Br.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By R.K. Brummitt.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial rhizomatous herbs; stem procumbent or climbing. White latex present. Leaves petiolate, variously lobed at the base. Flowers solitary, axillary, with a pair of large and sometimes inflated bracteoles partly or entirely concealing the sepals. Corolla large, infundibuliform or tubiform, glabrous or ciliate. Ovary glabrous, unilocular; ovules 4. Stigma bilobed; lobes swollen and elongate. Pollen grains pantoporate; exine more or less smooth.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   The genus differs constantly from{\i  Convolvulus} in its pollen grains and unilocular ovary, but the European species are most easily distinguished by the pair of broad bracteoles immediately below the sepals. The generic delimitation is discussed by W. H. Lewis & R. L. Oliver, {\i Ann. Missouri Bot. Gard.}{\b  52}: 217-222 (1965).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   A{\i  flore pleno} cultivar of{\i  C. pubescens} Lindley, from China, easily recognized by its pink flowers and oblong-hastate leaves, is widely cultivated and has sometimes persisted as a garden escape.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Hybrids may become well established by vegetative reproduction. White-flowered plants from S. Sweden which have been referred to {\b 3} are probably {\b 2}({\b a}) × {\b 4}; and glabrous pink-flowered plants with saccate bracteoles and a rounded leaf-sinus, well established in C. England (Nottinghamshire), may be {\b 3} × {\b 4}. {\b 2}({\b a}) × {\b 3} ({\i C}. × {\i lucana} (Ten.) G. Don) may be widespread in S. Europe and in the British Isles, but is often difficult to distinguish from one or other parent.
